Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.00,0:00:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,｢There was a hungry crow｣
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.00,0:00:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,｢Who wanted to get some feed｣
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.00,0:00:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,｢If only this beak were only longer｣
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.00,0:00:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,｢That feed would be a bit closer｣
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.00,0:01:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,｢A crow can think｣
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.00,0:01:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,｢can think... can think｣
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.00,0:01:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Observe, propose a hypothesis, experiment and consider results.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.00,0:01:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Learn the way of scientific thought.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.00,0:01:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We begin with a Thinking Observation.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.00,0:01:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Today we observe a strange pheonenon using coins.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.00,0:01:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Hold up a single one yen and two ten yen coins between your fingers.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.00,0:01:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This ten yen coin remains above.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.00,0:01:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The lower two coins drop.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.00,0:02:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The one yen coin above and the 10 yen coin below.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.00,0:02:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If we drop these two coins...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.00,0:02:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The one yen coin ends up on top.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.00,0:02:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Did they switch en route?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.00,0:02:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's do it once more.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.00,0:02:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Once more the one yen coin went to the bottom.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.00,0:02:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,As we thought they switched positions.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.00,0:02:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's try a different combination.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.00,0:02:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We add another 10 yen coin underneath.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.00,0:02:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Leaving the single ten yen coin above in place, we drop the three below.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.00,0:02:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Doing so, we confirm the three coins have changed position.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.00,0:02:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Will the one yen coin end up at the bottom?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.00,0:03:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The one yen coin ended up in the middle.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.00,0:03:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's try once more.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.00,0:03:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It's the same.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.00,0:03:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's try to organize this on paper.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.00,0:03:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,At the start 1 yen 10 yen became 10 yen 1 yen.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.00,0:03:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Next if we add another 10 yen coin below.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.00,0:03:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It changed this way.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.00,0:03:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We don't understand this well.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.00,0:03:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What will happen with a different arrangement.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.00,0:03:56.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This time we dropped the one yen coin in the middle.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.00,0:04:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And it ended up underneath.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.00,0:04:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's also confirm this on paper.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.00,0:04:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Looking carefully at the results..
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.00,0:04:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We can see some regularity.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.00,0:04:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Given that, what will happen with this arrangement?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.00,0:04:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Thinking Observation.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.00,0:06:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We will reveal the answer in the next program.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.00,0:06:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Today's problem uses a pendulum.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.00,0:06:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Grabbing the ball and release it.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.00,0:06:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, it swings well.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.00,0:06:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a pendulum.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.00,0:06:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, the pendulum we're using is special.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.00,0:06:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The weight at the end is a powerful magnet.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.00,0:06:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If we bring it close to a clip.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.00,0:06:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,it sticks to it firmly.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.00,0:06:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But here we have prepared an aluminum plate.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.00,0:07:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And to this
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.00,0:07:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,it doesn't stick at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.00,0:07:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Magnets don't stick to aluminum.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.00,0:07:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now this is the problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.00,0:07:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The aluminum plate that this magnet will not stick to
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.00,0:07:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we place it on the desk.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.00,0:07:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And we separate the magnet from it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.00,0:07:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If we do this how will the pendulum swing?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.00,0:07:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,1. It will go slower than the case with no plate.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.00,0:07:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and stop.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.00,0:07:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,2. Just the opposite. It will go faster and not stop at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.00,0:07:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,３｡\N3. It will swing the same as if there were no plate.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.00,0:07:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well then what will happen?\NWe'll present the anser at the end of the program.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.00,0:07:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone, please think hard won't you?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.00,0:08:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And now the answer from earlier.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.00,0:08:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone did you think carefully?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.00,0:08:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, let's do it for real.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.00,0:08:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,First we try the case without the plate beneath.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.00,0:08:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the normal state.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.00,0:08:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we try with the aluminum plate beneath.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.00,0:09:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How do you think the pendulum will swing?\NWatch really closely, won't you?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.00,0:09:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It stopped right away.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.00,0:09:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's try once more.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.00,0:09:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer is 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.00,0:09:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It was "the pendulum will swing more slowly than the case without the plate
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.00,0:09:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and stop right away."
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.00,0:09:34.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But magnest ought not stick to aluminum.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.00,0:09:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Why should this happen?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.00,0:09:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This is connected to a propery between magnets and aluminum.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.00,0:09:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Magnets don't stick to aluminum, but it conducts electricity.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.00,0:09:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And magnets and electricity...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.00,0:09:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,From here on we think for ourselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.00,0:09:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,From here on we're all thinking crows.
